t until recently it has attracted little scholarly attention. This book combines a study of the chronicle's sources, content, and methods of composition, with its manuscript contexts. Using the Anglo-Norman Oldest Version as a touchstone, it investigates the chronicle's social ideals, its representation of women, and its distinctive versions of such elements of British history as the Trojan foundation myth, the ruin of the Britons, the Norman Conquest, and Arthur and Merlin, arguing that its humane, populist vision demands reassessment of medieval popular understandings of British history, and of the presumed dominance of imperialism, next-worldly piety, misogyny, and a taste for violence in late-medieval culture. The book also analyses evidence for the production of the Anglo-Norman Brut, and examines the ways in which its makers and users reconstructed British history through manuscript context, ordinatio and apparatus, annotationand illustration. Julia Marvin is a Fellow of the Medieval Institute and Associate Professor in the Program of Liberal Studies at the University of Notre Dame.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aManuscripts, Anglo-Norman. 4aBibliography & Manuscripts. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Norman.  aArthurian.  aBibliography.  aBritish history.  aChronicle studies.  aEnglish.  aGalfridian.  aGeoffrey of Monmouth.  aHistoriography.  aMedieval Art.  aMedieval iterature: Medieval History.  aMedieval language.  aMedieval manuscript.  aMiddle Ages.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787440128423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787440128/original  a978